ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 3
 displays the surface morphology of the CA and CA/CQDs membranes. CA/CQDs membranes had higher surface pore size and porosity than that of CA membrane (Table 2
). The surface roughness (Table 2) follows the same trend as surface porosity, where CA+1000 CQDs membrane had the highest surface porosity and roughness of 4.02 ± 0.37% and 6.68 ± 0.76 nm, respectively. However, increasing the concentration of CQDs from 1000 to 3000 ppm, the surface porosity and roughness were reduced from 4.02 ± 0.37 to 2.73 ± 0.19% and 6.68 ± 0.76 to 5.59 ± 0.47 nm, respectively. Adding CQDs in CA solution enhanced the polymer viscosity (Table 1), causing the demixing rate of solvent and non-solvent slow down. The increased viscosity was caused by the hydrogen bonding between CA and CQDs [42,61]. These hydrogen bonding was proved by FTIR spectra (Fig. S6) of the membrane, where there was a shift of peaks for C-O-C, C-O and C=O vibration. The CA polymer chain interacts with the carboxyl and hydroxyl groups of CQDs, where CQDs acts as the bridge, resulting in entanglement of CA chains. Furthermore, the presence of hydrophilic CQDs caused the formation of a pseudo water layer on the membrane surface [69, 70]. Using 1000 ppm of CQDs, this pseudo water layer formation increases the probability of attracting more water into the polymer solution, leading to faster inflow of water. However, for more than 1000 ppm of CQDs, the effective diffusivity of the polymer solution was decreased (Table 3
), where the diffusivity of the non-solvent declined while the inflow of water also slowed down. This would be further explained on the later part. Therefore, increasing the concentration of CQDs for over 1000 ppm could reduce the surface porosity of the CA/CQDs membrane [71,72].
